Barack Obama is the fourth President of the United States to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
The diploma, the medal and the $1.4 million cheque will receive them, among other things, for the exceptional effort to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will arrive at the Norwegian metropolitan in the morning and will have a lot to do.
First, a visit to the Nobel Institute, where for the first time he will meet with the five members of the committee that, in October, chose him between 172 people and 33 organizations.
After that, the presidential couple has scheduled a meeting with Norwegian king Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
The visit will culminate with a ceremony in which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive him, although the third will receive him in his office.
The White House has already announced that, after receiving the prize, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid this issue, knowing that he is receiving the prize as president of a country that is currently in war in two countries.
His war efforts increased even more with the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which does not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, the diploma and the cheque of ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million Czech crowns).
It is proposed to give them charitable paraffins, but it has not yet decided to which organization in particular.
During his full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet to which they will attend, in addition to the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and another 250 guests.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude towards the prize.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling of not deserving it at all.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for everyone who struggle for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents “a challenge to take action.”
