US: Repeat is the Mother of Wisdom
It is comic that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the most intelligent man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan issue the strategy of his predecessor, which he himself took for the most stupid.
When he finally revealed his Afghan approach, hoped with anxiety, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only in the same text the phrase "like in Iraq" is used several times, but it has also not failed to use the title of Bush's January 2007 declaration for his own declaration: "A new way forward."
He himself, who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering by the civil war.
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful, so that today nothing is spoken about Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation didn't improve, but objectively left his successor a much more favorable initial situation than he could expect.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to be repeated.
The camp captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the captain-in-chief of the Afghan operation general Stanley McCristal. He, even despite the traditional subordinate relations, subjected the indecised gunmen in the White House to a hard criticism.
He asked 40,000 people to improve the situation.
The president vacillated for three months, but nothing better happened to him, so at least he deceived the general about 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to make Europe promise to him another 5,000, although he himself previously counted at least 10,000.
The most problematic of all Obama’s strategy seems to be his goal, starting to withdraw the troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and ending this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase gives the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fraternal wars in recent years, the Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: it is not possible to trust anyone and no agreement is fulfilled.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinaryly complicated due to confused relationships, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even setting a state that is “capable of action”, a minimum goal of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy is shocked by his volunteerism.
During the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who doesn’t know anything about reality, can believe that the soldiers sent to the war so that they’ll “return home soon”, will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, fixing the date of the withdrawal of the troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will consider it as an indirect declaration of the U.S. defeat.
The last NATO summit demonstrated that Europeans are increasingly less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians don’t know, nor want to explain to their voters, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of the events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and increased sanctions do not have any effect on the Iranians, the U.S. will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for the answers exactly when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphal withdrawal of the troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic reverse for the situation in Afghanistan.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left for the presidential election and therefore there is still a lot of time to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
