This year women received the Nobel Prize in all categories less Physics
Five women, which is a record figure, received today in Stockholm from the hands of King Charles XVI Gustave of Sweden the Nobel Prizes of this year, in specialized categories and in literature.
In addition to the four scientists, among the awards was also a German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller.
The Nobel Prize in Medicine was awarded to two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, as well as their compatriot Jack Szostak for research in the field of chromosomes.
The Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to the Israeli Ada Jonath and the Americans Venkatraman Ramakrishna and Thomas Steitz for the explanation of the structure and function of the ribosomes.
The latest award, the Nobel Prize in Economics, was awarded to the American Elinor Ostrom and her compatriot Oliver Williamson for the analysis of an economic report.
The only specialized category, without a woman awarded, was Physics.
This award was awarded today by scientists Charles Kao for the research in the field of optical cables, and George Smith and Willard Boyle for the invention of the CCD chip, which constitutes the basis of all digital cameras, fax or telescopes.
Each prize winner collected the diploma, the Nobel medal and the certificate of the money received.
This sum in each category is up to ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 25 million Czech crowns).
In the event that there are several awards in each category, the prize is distributed to each other.
