A Czech Discovery: An Effective Substance Even In 'Called' HIV Virus
The team of Czech and German scientists test new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this enhanced substance is the fact that it is also effective against drugs-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some medications are already available.
AIDS cannot be cured so far.
However, the life of patients can be significantly extended thanks to a mixture of medications that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, the so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, medications no longer work.
The work of the experts of three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of dominating the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that the substances called metalocarborans have an effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are compounds of bor, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way than all the drugs used today, and therefore they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work the scientists find new, ‘better’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the albumin of the virus.
Metalocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyder cages composed of the bore, hydrogen and carbon atoms are united by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A traitor and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and it is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, there is no fraction of the HIV virus and mature and infectious corpuscles of the virus would not be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we stop also the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
