Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiation text to focus on what the UN top climate official, Yvo de Bóer, described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 25 to 45 per cent by 2020, compared to the 1990 levels, while major developing countries would cut their emissions during the same period between 15 and 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also encouraged talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, on Friday the same class of verbal artificial fires that have dominated conversations last week was presented.
