Management Revolution or End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the major French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with respect to their employers reminds the position of companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about that collaborators adhere to "values" determined from above as before it was about imposing consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer in the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the market conquest strategies... although the authority temptation to impose products that are not related to the customer’s preference factors is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in a mortal desmoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the peak of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) “ requires that all stakeholders [...] have a proactive behavior and a prospective vision”; this requires from the employees a commitment that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authority management.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist in putting the collaborators at the center of the concerns of the company as well as the customer.
Internal opinion surveys have a relative benefit.
Will internal opinion surveys, such as the Orange questionnaire among its employees, encourage the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I am afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, facing a new situation, and after many rounds, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Secondly, because authority, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
Lastly, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the major engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanically.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the ancient conductist theory that American "neurosciences" reactivated recently, and that the Studies and the media spread widely behind them.
In this way, suggesting that it is possible to handle the “commands” (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent Ipsos research published on Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a mechanicist management posture, unadapted to the world of today.
Identifying and measuring mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises, implies adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating in every reasoning or business management practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, the commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from Motifunctional Analysis adopt this concept of employees’ motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined dox that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, corporate managers can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and re-locate the management of human waste “on the place”.
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
