The Count of the Dinosaur
The Tawa hallae had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-metre long and 1.50-metre high animal running over the two strong backs, had an extended head with sharp teeth and curved, short arms with hoz-shaped garras and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of millions of years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the Science magazine on Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea in the Ecuador.
Tawa opened a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogy relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation in Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we’ve found in a day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for triastic sediments, reports Randall Irmis member of the team of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
During the excavation, the remains of five specimens were gathered in total.
A finding confirms the theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Indians Hopi.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional discovery: "Triasic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current opinion, the dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, about when the saurios divided into their three most important genealogy lines: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithischia herbívoros (saurios with bird pelvis), to which belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the crane of Tawa, the researchers found indications of air bags, such as those that also own the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa also the bones of the spine were obviously partially full of air.
Tawa is the oldest and primitive airbags theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the emparent line of the subsequent giant sauropods also owned light air bags and bones, the common ancestors of both groups were likely to already produce this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers deduce that saurians arose there for the first time.
Consequently, the three genealogical lines separated at the beginning and spread from South America through all corners of the Earth, which then still formed a unique earth mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa finds the remains of two other theropods not very intimate.
The three cannot descend from a single parent ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migration waves have been given to North America, says Alan Turner from the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
There are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a brother group of dinosaurs, lived in today’s Poland, says Bonn’s paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while in other continents there is barely something to discover.
The question of how the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare side line of the reptiles to the dominant Earth vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triasic the dinosaurs still shared their life space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of current cocodrils and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
At the end of the Triasic the dinosaurs expanded around the world and many new species developed, while the relatives extincted at the border of the Triasic to the Jurassic.
Successful stories were not eternal.
There are two possibilities to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
It could have been given a mass extinction to which dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so these could overcome the counterparts in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteor impact stopped the rise of a group of species, which had already evolved in the Triasic and since then had a miserable existence: the mammals.
