Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women from younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study ‘Fecundity and Traffic of Women in Spain’, elaborated by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 does not leave any doubts about this: 75% of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to maternity.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of the coexistence in a couple and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job, initiate the coexistence in a couple, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and maternity, and have less descendence.
“Women between 35 and 49 years with fixed work have the first child, average, 3.7 years after initiating the coexistence, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their vital trajectory to get them, which has led them to postpon the union and the arrival of the children.
In addition, the type of work performed exercises a lot of influence on maternity although less on the schedule of parenting," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of studies is another of the factors that differentiate the age of women by marrying and having the first wardrobe.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the higher the age they marry and the first child they have.
The difference remains among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those who have elementary and higher studies have been mothers for the first time at the 25.1 and 32.1 average respectively.
“There is also another division between women based on their level of studies.
While those who have elementary studies marry and have their first child before getting a stable job, those of middle or higher levels invest this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a condition prior to marriage and the arrival of a child,” Delgado says.
