Emergency removal is mandatory.
As it happened with the ABS brake anti-block and will pass with the ESP stability control, emergency brake assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, it is already in all new-matriculated tourism and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a period of lack is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, by their way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency brake assistant what it does is to increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the brake that the driver gives.
But this does not always keep that pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not reached the brake before the collision and half of them did not take all the strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in turn, requires the maximum to the brake system, reducing the distance the car uses to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 deadly accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided a year.
The reduction will be even greater – it is estimated that one in four human damage accidents would be avoided – when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects the obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps you by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
